    Here's the deal.\
If you're looking for an anime that'll get you thinking, or an anime you can watch to settle down before bedtime, you'd be better off with something like Mushishi. If you want a considerably well-crafted rollercoaster ride, Baccano is right here waiting for you.\
The main asset of any anime is its characters. Baccano is a particularly impressive example of a good set of characters, ranging from complete maniacs (Ladd Russo) to Jessie-and-James-soundalikes (Isaac and Miria) to strangely relatable pussies (Jacuzzi Splot). Not all of them are good guys - a few of them are complete arseholes - but they're all well constucted and\
          \
        bounce off of each other awesomely. I could talk about each one and their place in the series in general, but there are SO GOD DAMN MANY characters that I wouldn't know where to even start, so I'm moving on.\
In terms of art and animation, it's solid. It's no lavish visual maverick, like Gankutsuou, but it's vivid and rich enough to be a good counterpoint to the events taking place.\
As for the elephant in the room... you'd be better off with the dub. It just feels way more natural to hear American voice actors performing American roles. It's one of those rare few dubs that's always brought up to defend dubs in those ubiquitous \"sub-v-dub\" arguments, and for good reason. It's often considered one of the best dubs of all time. It's not like I'd disagree or anything ^_^  \
The story is notorious for its wonky presentation. To avoid spoilers, the majority of Baccano takes place on one locomotive, in which many events take place around the same time. To cover all of this, the point of view switches from character to character, not always in chronological order, revealing more and more aspects of the plot with every episode. Some have called it confusing. I call it brilliant. It keeps secrets from you, leaving you wondering what certain characters' motivations are, then revealing them by the next episode while managing to make you ask even MORE questions, only for those to be revealed.\
Baccano is loud, fast and fun. It's not particularly intellectual, but that's fine because it isn't trying to be. It's no Elfen Lied, an anime that shoots for depth of character and narrative that simply ends up as manipulative. It's designed around enjoyment, pure and simple. Considering that, the amount of memorable characters, unique method of storytelling and impressive historical accuracies all make this series one of the most solid series ever made. \
(also unless you hate jazz the soundtrack is really good too!!!!!!)\
